\\n**Suggested improvement (optional):** A combined `ReadForWrite` method that returns both the `(ref, entries)` tuple and the parsed trail data in one pass would eliminate the redundancy, but the real-world savings are negligible:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc (s *Store) readForWrite(trailID ID) (*plumbing.Reference, map[string]object.TreeEntry, *Metadata, *Discussion, *Checkpoints, error)\\n```\\n\\nThis would let `AddCheckpoint`, `Update`, and similar methods avoid the double tree walk. Not urgent.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 2: Store.FindByBranch does a full List() scan\\n\\n**Impact: LOW (currently), MEDIUM at scale**\\n\\n**What happens:** `FindByBranch` at `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail/store.go:222` calls `List()` which:\\n1. Calls `getBranchTree()` -- resolves ref, gets commit, gets tree\\n2. Calls `FlattenTree()` -- recursively walks the entire tree into a flat map\\n3. Iterates ALL entries, finds `metadata.json` files\\n4. For each metadata file: reads the blob, decodes JSON\\n5. Then the caller iterates all decoded metadata to match `Branch == branchName`\\n\\nFor N trails, this reads and decodes N metadata blobs to find one.\\n\\n**Why LOW currently:** A typical developer has perhaps 5-20 trails. Reading and decoding 20 small JSON blobs is sub-millisecond. The sharded directory structure (`trailID[:2]/trailID[2:]`) means even the tree walk is bounded.\\n\\n**Why MEDIUM at scale:** In a team scenario with hundreds of trails or in a long-lived repo, this linear scan grows. An index file (e.g., `_index.json` mapping branch->trailID) would make this O(1) for branch lookup.\\n\\n**Suggested improvement:** If scale becomes an issue, add an `_index.json` file to the trails branch that maps `branch -> trailID`. Update it on Write/Delete. For now, the linear scan is acceptable.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 3: appendCheckpointToTrail runs during the post-commit hook condensation path\\n\\n**Impact: LOW-MEDIUM**\\n\\n**What happens in the hot path** (lines 1011-1018 of `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go`):\\n\\nAfter `CondenseSession` completes:\\n1. **`appendCheckpointToTrail`** (line 1012):\\n   - `GetCurrentBranchName(repo)` -- reads HEAD ref\\n   - `GetDefaultBranchName(repo)` -- scans branch refs\\n   - `store.FindByBranch(branchName)` -- full `List()` scan (Finding 2)\\n   - `store.AddCheckpoint(...)` -- `Read()` + `Write()` (Finding 1) = 2 tree reads + 1 tree build + 1 commit\\n2. **`generateTrailTitleFromTranscript`** (line 1017, see Finding 4)\\n\\nThe `appendCheckpointToTrail` cost is: 2 ref lookups + 3 tree traversals + N blob decodes (from FindByBranch) + 1 tree build + 1 commit creation. All local git operations against the packfile/loose objects.\\n\\n**Why LOW-MEDIUM:** This is synchronous in the post-commit hook. With a handful of trails, total wall time is likely 5-20ms on a warm filesystem. However, this runs on EVERY commit that has a checkpoint trailer, and it's doing 3 separate tree traversals of the same small tree. More importantly, `FindByBranch` doing a full scan when `AddCheckpoint` will read the same trail again immediately after is wasteful.\\n\\n**Suggested improvement:** Pass the already-known branch name and trail metadata from `FindByBranch` directly to `AddCheckpoint`, avoiding the redundant `Read()` inside `AddCheckpoint`. Or refactor the function to accept the trail metadata looked up by the caller:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc appendCheckpointToTrail(repo *git.Repository, cpID id.CheckpointID, commitSHA plumbing.Hash, prompts []string, branchName string) {\\n    // Caller already knows branch. Skip GetCurrentBranchName/GetDefaultBranchName.\\n    store := trail.NewStore(repo)\\n    existing, err := store.FindByBranch(branchName)\\n    if err != nil || existing == nil {\\n        return\\n    }\\n    // ... rest\\n}\\n```\\n\\nOr better yet, since `condenseAndUpdateState` already calls `GetCurrentBranchName` on line 1015, pass the branch name in