itions, a Haiku API call takes 1-3 seconds. This adds 1-3 seconds to every post-commit hook on the first commit of a trail (when `Body == \\\"\\\"`).\\n\\n**Mitigation factors:**\\n- The `existing.Body != \\\"\\\"` guard at line 2249 means this only runs once per trail (first condensation)\\n- The `settings.IsSummarizeEnabled()` check at line 2240 allows users to disable it\\n- It's best-effort (errors are silently logged)\\n\\n**Why HIGH impact:** Even once per trail, adding 1-3 seconds of network latency to a commit hook is noticeable. If the API is down or the user is offline, this could hang the hook. The `context.Background()` with no timeout is a correctness bug.\\n\\n**Suggested improvements:**\\n1. **Add a timeout context** -- at minimum, wrap with `context.WithTimeout(ctx, 5*time.Second)`\\n2. **Run asynchronously** -- spawn a goroutine and don't wait. The trail title is non-critical metadata. The goroutine writes to the trails branch independently. This removes the API call entirely from the commit hot path.\\n3. **Defer to a background job** -- queue the title generation and process it later (e.g., on next `entire trail list` or as a background task).\\n\\n```go\\n// Option 2: fire-and-forget goroutine\\nif branchName != \\\"\\\" && branchName != GetDefaultBranchName(repo) && len(result.Transcript) > 0 {\\n    go generateTrailTitleFromTranscript(repo, branchName, result.Transcript, result.FilesTouched, state.AgentType)\\n}\\n```\\n\\nHowever, note that go-git's `Repository` object may not be safe for concurrent use, so the goroutine approach would need to open its own repo handle. A timeout is the simpler fix.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 5: fetchTrailsBranch() does a synchronous network fetch on every `trail list`\\n\\n**Impact: MEDIUM**\\n\\n**What happens:** At line 573 of `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail_cmd.go`, `fetchTrailsBranch()` runs `git fetch origin +refs/heads/entire/trails:refs/remotes/origin/entire/trails` synchronously with a 10-second timeout. This runs on EVERY `entire trail list` invocation.\\n\\n**Why MEDIUM:** On a good network, `git fetch` for a single ref takes 200-500ms. On a poor network (VPN, satellite, airplane mode), it can take up to the full 10-second timeout before the user sees any output. The function is best-effort (errors are silenced), which is good, but the timeout is on the high side.\\n\\n**Mitigation factors:**\\n- 10-second timeout prevents infinite hangs\\n- `GIT_TERMINAL_PROMPT=0` prevents auth prompts\\n- The data is still available from the last fetch if offline\\n\\n**Suggested improvements:**\\n1. **Reduce timeout to 3-5 seconds** -- for a single-ref fetch, 10 seconds is generous\\n2. **Run in the background** -- start the fetch, proceed with listing local data, and only merge remote data if the fetch completes before the local listing is done\\n3. **Cache with staleness** -- only fetch if the last fetch was more than N minutes ago (e.g., check a timestamp file in `.git/`)\\n4. **Make it opt-in** -- add a `--no-fetch` flag or a `--fetch` flag (default to local-only)\\n\\n```go\\n// Option 2: background fetch with local-first display\\ndone := make(chan struct{})\\ngo func() {\\n    defer close(done)\\n    fetchTrailsBranch()\\n}()\\n// List local trails immediately\\ntrails, err := store.List()\\n// Optionally wait a short time for remote data\\nselect {\\ncase <-done:\\n    // Remote fetched, re-list to include remote trails\\n    trails, err = store.List()\\ncase <-time.After(500 * time.Millisecond):\\n    // Use local data, fetch will complete in background\\n}\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 6: Store.Write always rebuilds the entire tree from all entries\\n\\n**Impact: LOW**\\n\\n**What happens:** `Write()` calls `getBranchEntries()` which flattens the ENTIRE trails branch tree into a map, then modifies 3 entries (metadata.json, discussion.json, checkpoints.json), then calls `BuildTreeFromEntries()` which rebuilds the complete tree from scratch.\\n\\n**Why LOW:** `BuildTreeFromEntries` builds git tree objects from a flat map. For a trails branch with N trails, that's ~3N entries. Git trees are small (a few hundred bytes each). The tree-building algorithm groups entries by directory prefix and creates subtrees recursively. Even with 100 trails (300 entries), this is sub-millisecond computation. The main cost is writing the new tree objects to git's object store, which is also fast (local disk, small objects).\\n\\nThe alternative would be incremental tree updates (modify only the changed subtree and reconstruct parents). This is significantly more complex code for negligible performance gain at realistic trail counts.\\n\\n**Suggested improvement:** Not warranted at current scale. If trail counts reach thousands, consider go-git's tree builder with incremental updates, or a path-based tree mutation that only rebuilds affected parent trees.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 7: Unnecessary work in appendCheckpointToTrail\\n\\n**Impact: LOW-MEDIUM**\\n\\n**What happens:** At lines 2275-2281 of `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go`:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc appendCheckpointToTrail(repo *git.Repository, cpID id.CheckpointID, commitSHA plumbing.Hash, prompts []string) {\\n    branchName := GetCurrentBranchName(repo)     // reads HEAD ref, iterates branches\\n    if branchName == \\\"\\\" {\\n        return\\n    }\\n    defaultBranch := GetDefaultBranchName(repo)   // scans branch refs for main/master\\n    if branchName == defaultBranch {\\n        return\\n    }\\n    // ...\\n}\\n```\\n\\nBut the **caller** at line 1015-1016 already does:\\n```go\\nbranchName := GetCurrentBranchName(repo)\\nif branchName != \\\"\\\" && branchName != GetDefaultBranchName(repo) ...\\n```\\n\\nSo `GetCurrentBranchName` is called twice and `GetDefaultBranchName` is called twice. Additionally, `generateTrailTitleFromTranscript` at line 2244 calls `store.FindByBranch(branchName)`, and `appendCheckpointToTrail` at line 2285 also calls `store.FindByBranch(branchName)` -- so `FindByBranch` (which does the full `List()` scan) is called twice for the same branch.\\n\\n**Total redundant work in condenseAndUpdateState trail path:**\\n- `GetCurrentBranchName`: called 2x (line 1015 and line 2275)\\n- `GetDefaultBranchName`: called 2x (line 1016 and line 2279)\\n- `FindByBranch`: called 2x (line 2244 in generateTrailTitleFromTranscript and line 2285 in appendCheckpointToTrail) -- each does a full tree flatten + all metadata decodes\\n- Total: 4 extra tree traversals of the trails branch that could be eliminated\\n\\n**Suggested improvement:** Refactor `condenseAndUpdateState` to do the branch lookups once and pass results down:\\n\\n```go\\nbranchName := GetCurrentBranchName(repo)\\nif branchName == \\\"\\\" || branchName == GetDefaultBranchName(repo) {\\n    return true // skip trail operations on default branch\\n}\\n\\nstore := trail.NewStore(repo)\\nexisting, err := store.FindByBranch(branchName)\\nif err != nil || existing == nil {\\n    return true // no trail for this branch\\n}\\n\\n// Link checkpoint to trail\\nappendCheckpointToExistingTrail(store, existing.TrailID, result.CheckpointID, head.Hash(), result.Prompts)\\n\\n// Generate title if needed (only once, when Body is empty)\\nif existing.Body == \\\"\\\" && len(result.Transcript) > 0 {\\n    generateTrailTitleForTrail(store, existing, result.Transcript, result.FilesTouched, state.AgentType)\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis reduces the trail operations from ~6 tree traversals to ~1 (the initial `FindByBranch`).\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 8: Two new Store operations in the condensation hot path -- combined profile\\n\\n**Impact: MEDIUM (due to Finding 4)**\\n\\n**Summary of the condensation hot path additions:**\\n\\nThe `condenseAndUpdateState` function (lines 990-1047) now has this post-condensation work:\\n\\n| Operation | Estimated cost | Notes |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| `appendCheckpointToTrail` | ~5-15ms | 3 tree traversal