Finding 4: `hasFlag()` Parsing `os.Args` Directly\\n\\n**Severity: Medium**\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail_cmd.go`, line 463\\n\\n```go\\nfunc hasFlag(name string) bool {\\n    for _, arg := range os.Args {\\n        if arg == \\\"--\\\"+name || strings.HasPrefix(arg, \\\"--\\\"+name+\\\"=\\\") {\\n            return true\\n        }\\n    }\\n    return false\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis function bypasses cobra's flag parsing infrastructure entirely by scanning raw `os.Args`. Problems:\\n\\n1. **Fragile to aliasing**: If cobra defines short flags (`-t` for `--title`), `hasFlag` won't detect them.\\n2. **Fragile to subcommand nesting**: It scans ALL args, including the command name and subcommands. If `os.Args` were `[\\\"entire\\\", \\\"--title\\\", \\\"trail\\\", \\\"create\\\"]`, it would match `--title` even though it belongs to a different command in the chain.\\n3. **Breaks testability**: Unit tests cannot override `os.Args` without process-global mutation (and as noted in CLAUDE.md, `t.Setenv`/`os.Setenv` and `t.Parallel()` don't mix).\\n\\nCobra provides `cmd.Flags().Changed(\\\"title\\\")` which returns whether a flag was explicitly set on the command line (as opposed to using the default). This is the idiomatic way to distinguish \\\"flag not provided\\\" from \\\"flag provided with empty value\\\" in cobra. The `cmd *cobra.Command` is available in the `RunE` closure and could be passed down.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 5: Stringly-Typed Status Validation\\n\\n**Severity: Low**\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail/trail.go`, lines 64-96\\n\\nThe `Status` type is defined as `type Status string` with constants and an `IsValid()` method that loops through `ValidStatuses()`. This is a reasonable pattern for Go. The validation is centralized in the `trail` package, and all call sites use `status.IsValid()`:\\n\\n- `trail_cmd.go:129` (list filter)\\n- `trail_cmd.go:262` (create)\\n- `trail_cmd.go:426` (update)\\n\\nThe `IsValid()` method iterates `ValidStatuses()` each time, but with only 6 statuses this is negligible. No real issue here -- the pattern is idiomatic Go for string enums and the validation is properly centralized. The `formatValidStatuses()` helper in `trail_cmd.go` (line 482) produces the user-facing error string. This is fine.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 6: `Store.FindByBranch` Does a Full `List()` Scan\\n\\n**Severity: Low**\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail/store.go`, line 222\\n\\n```go\\nfunc (s *Store) FindByBranch(branchName string) (*Metadata, error) {\\n    trails, err := s.List()\\n    if err != nil {\\n        return nil, err\\n    }\\n    for _, t := range trails {\\n        if t.Branch == branchName {\\n            return t, nil\\n        }\\n    }\\n    return nil, nil\\n}\\n```\\n\\n`List()` flattens the entire git tree, reads every `metadata.json` blob, and decodes them all. For the expected data size (one trail per branch, maybe 10-100 branches in a typical repo), this is acceptable. Git object reads are local and fast.\\n\\nHowever, `FindByBranch` is called in several hot paths:\\n- `appendCheckpointToTrail` (every commit with a checkpoint trailer)\\n- `generateTrailTitleFromTranscript` (every first condensation)\\n- `runTrailShow` (every `entire trail` invocation)\\n\\nEach call does O(N) deserialization of all trails. If trail count grows to hundreds (possible in large monorepos with many short-lived feature branches), this could become noticeable. A secondary index (e.g., a `branch-index.json` mapping branch names to trail IDs) would allow O(1) lookup, but this is premature optimization at current scale.\\n\\nMore concerning: `FindByBranch` is called TWICE per commit in `condenseAndUpdateState` -- once by `appendCheckpointToTrail` (line 2285) and once by `generateTrailTitleFromTranscript` (line 2244). Each call does a full `List()`. This is a low-hanging optimization: pass the trail metadata from the first lookup to the second.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 7: `Store.Write` Reads and Rewrites Entire Tree\\n\\n**Severity: Low-to-Medium**\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail/store.go`, line 67\\n\\n```go\\nfunc (s *Store) Write(metadata *Metadata, discussion *Discussion, checkpoints *Checkpoints) error {\\n    // ...\\n    ref, entries, err := s.getBranchEntries()  // Flattens ENTIRE tree\\n    // ... add/update entries for this trail ...\\n    newTreeHash, err := checkpoint.BuildTreeFromEntries(s.repo, entries)  // Rebuilds ENTIRE tree\\n    // ...\\n}\\n```\\n\\nEvery `Write` call (1) flattens the entire trails branch tree into memory, (2) modifies 3 entries, and (3) rebuilds the entire tree from scratch. `Update` calls `Read` + `Write`, meaning it flattens+rebuilds the tree twice. `AddCheckpoint` does the same: `Read` + modify + `Write`.\\n\\nFor the expected data size (10-100 trails, each with 3 files = 30-300 tree entries), this is fine. Git objects are content-addressable, so unchanged blobs are deduplicated automatically. The tree rebuild is O(N) in entries but N is small.\\n\\nThe real concern is that `AddCheckpoint` is called on every commit (from `appendCheckpointToTrail` in the post-commit hook). Combined with Finding 6 (full `List()` scan in `FindByBranch`), a single commit triggers: `List()` (all trails) + `Read()` (one trail, 3 blobs) + `Write()` (flatten + rebuild entire tree). This is ~4 tree traversals per commit. At hundreds of trails, this could add measurable latency to the post-commit hook.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 8: Redundant Branch Name Resolution in `appendCheckpointToTrail`\\n\\n**Severity: Medium**\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go`, lines 1011-1018 and 2274-2281\\n\\nThe caller `condenseAndUpdateState` at line 1015 already calls `GetCurrentBranchName(repo)` and `GetDefaultBranchName(repo)` immediately after `appendCheckpointToTrail`:\\n\\n```go\\n// Line 1012\\nappendCheckpointToTrail(repo, result.CheckpointID, head.Hash(), result.Prompts)\\n\\n// Line 1015-1017\\nbranchName := GetCurrentBranchName(repo)\\nif branchName != \\\"\\\" && branchName != GetDefaultBranchName(repo) && len(result.Transcript) > 0 {\\n    generateTrailTitleFromTranscript(repo, branchName, result.Transcript, result.FilesTouched, state.AgentType)\\n}\\n```\\n\\nBut `appendCheckpointToTrail` internally also calls both:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc appendCheckpointToTrail(repo *git.Repository, cpID id.CheckpointID, commitSHA plumbing.Hash, prompts []string) {\\n    branchName := GetCurrentBranchName(repo)     // REDUNDANT\\n    if branchName == \\\"\\\" {\\n        return\\n    }\\n    defaultBranch := GetDefaultBranchName(repo)   // REDUNDANT\\n    if branchName == defaultBranch {\\n        return\\n    }\\n    // ...\\n}\\n```\\n\\nAnd `generateTrailTitleFromTranscript` also calls `FindByBranch` internally (line 2244), which is the same lookup `appendCheckpointToTrail` already did (line 2285).\\n\\nSo in total, a single `condenseAndUpdateState` call triggers:\\n- 3x `GetCurrentBranchName(repo)` (appendCheckpoint, generateTrailTitle, condenseAndUpdateState)\\n- 3x `GetDefaultBranchName(repo)` (same three callers)\\n- 2x `store.FindByBranch(branchName)` (appendCheckpoint + generateTrailTitle)\\n- Each `FindByBranch` calls `List()` which flattens the entire tree\\n\\nThe branch name resolution is cheap (just reading HEAD ref), but the double `FindByBranch` is wasteful. Both functions should accept the branch name and trail metadata as parameters rather than re-resolving them.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 9: `fetchTrailsBranch()` on Every `trail list`\\n\\n**Severity: Medium**\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail_cmd.go`, line 573\\n\\n```go\\nfunc fetchTrailsBranch() {\\n    ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), 10*time.Second)\\n    defer cancel()\\n    branchName := paths.TrailsBranchName\\n    refSpec := fmt.Sprintf(\\\"+refs/heads/%s:refs/remotes/origin/%s\\\", branchName, branchName)\\n    cmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, \\\"git\\\", \\\"fetch\\\", \\\"origin\\\", refSpec)\\n    cmd.Stdin = nil\\n    cmd.Env = append(os.Environ(), \\\"GIT_TERMINAL_PROMPT=0\\\")\\n    _ = cmd.Run()\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis spawns a `git fetch` subprocess with a 10-second timeout on every `entire trail list` invocation. Concerns:\\n\\n1. **Latency**: Network I/O on every list command adds 200ms-10s depending on network conditions. For a CLI tool, this is surprising UX. `git branch` and `gh pr list` both require explicit `--fetch` or assume local data.\\n2. **Offline usage**: When offline, the 10-second timeout will fire on every invocation before the list can be displayed, making the command feel broken.\\n3. **Implicit side effects**: A read-only list command silently modifies local refs (`refs/remotes/origin/...`). This violates the principle of least surprise.\\n\\nThe function is also called from `runTrailListAll`, which is triggered by `runTrailShow` when no trail exists for the current branch (line 63). So even `entire trail` (no subcommand) can trigger a network fetch.\\n\\nRecommendation: Make fetch explicit (e.g., `entire trail list --fetch` or `entire trail fetch`) or add a staleness check (only fetch if remote ref is older than N minutes).\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 10: Error Swallowing / `//nolint:errcheck` Annotations\\n\\n**Severity: Low-to-Medium (varies by instance)**\\n\\nAudit of all `//nolint:errcheck` and error-swallowing patterns in the new code:\\n\\n**trail_cmd.go:214** -- `_, currentBranch, _ := IsOnDefaultBranch(context.Background()) //nolint:errcheck`\\n- **Justified.** This is best-effort detection. If it fails, `currentBranch` is empty string and the subsequent logic handles that. The error return is unused but harmless.\\n\\n**trail_cmd.go:583** -- `_ = cmd.Run() //nolint:errcheck // best-effort fetch`\\n- **Justified.** Network fetch